    <!-- What is it -->
    <h2>What Is Glitch Text?</h2>
    <p>Glitch text — also known as <strong>zalgo text</strong>, corrupted text, or cursed text — is created by stacking Unicode combining diacritical marks on top of regular characters. Unicode includes hundreds of these marks (originally designed for languages that need accents, vowel marks, or tone indicators), and when you stack dozens of them on a single letter, the result overflows the normal line boundaries.</p>
    <p>The visual effect resembles corrupted data, digital glitches, or creepy horror text. The name "zalgo" comes from a 2009 internet creepypasta meme about a dark entity named Zalgo who corrupts everything he touches. The phrase "he comes" written in corrupted text became the signature zalgo meme.</p>
    <p>Unlike custom fonts or images, glitch text is real Unicode text — you can copy it, paste it, search it, and it works on virtually any device or platform. The combining characters are part of the Unicode standard, so they render correctly on all modern systems.</p>

    <!-- Technical -->
    <h2>How Combining Characters Work</h2>
    <p>Unicode defines three categories of combining marks used in glitch text:</p>
    <div class="how-grid" style="margin-top:16px;">
      <div class="how-step" style="text-align:left;">
        <h4>⬆️ Above (Stacking Up)</h4>
        <p>Marks like combining acute accent (U+0301), combining tilde (U+0303), combining overline (U+0305). These stack above the base character and create the "reaching upward" effect.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="how-step" style="text-align:left;">
        <h4>➡️ Middle (Overlay)</h4>
        <p>Marks like combining long stroke (U+0336), combining short solidus (U+0337). These overlay through the middle of the character, creating strikethrough chaos.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="how-step" style="text-align:left;">
        <h4>⬇️ Below (Dripping Down)</h4>
        <p>Marks like combining cedilla (U+0327), combining low line (U+0332). These extend below the baseline, creating the "dripping" or "melting" effect.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- FAQ -->
